story:
Paul Dennis was a much loved Husband, Dad and Grandad. 

In June 2019 Paul was Diagnosed with Bowel Cancer. Paul underwent two rounds of Chemotherapy and a round of Radiotherapy over the next 18 months, however his lost his brave battle in December 2020 surrounded by his family.

We would like to raise money for Macmillan for their support and kindness towards the end of Pauls illness.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My dad after a long fight against illness passed away on Boxing Day this year. He had a major scare a few years ago. Found out he had cancer in his left lung, and they operated and removed half of his lung. They told us the odds were massively against him surviving, but he managed to do that. 

During that difficult time my dad spent a lot of time with the Macmillian nurses. They were amazing with him, picked him up when he was struggling, when he was worried about his finances they helped him sort out what help he could get. We cannot thank you enough for everything you did for him.

story:
We have decided to raise money for Macmillan cancer support in memory of Julia Hardaker (my lovely Mum)!

Mum was admitted to hospital on 5th November, and received a diagnosis of bone and brain metastasis secondary to breast cancer. This was a shock to all of us and during the short illness that ensued my Mum, Dad and I received exemplarary care and support from the Macmillan nurses. They enabled Mum to be cared for at home right until the end on the 7th December respecting her wishes to remain at home with minimal intervention from healthcare professionals. They provided an excellent support structure when needed the most.

In lieu of floral tributes and bearing in mind the limited numbers allowed at the church we feel this is a good way for people to pay their respects. 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

pageSummaryWhat: I am facing my fear of public challenges
story:
Macmillan is a wonderful organisation. Their work is broad and far reaching, and for those who experience the impact of cancer they are a source of constant support. 

I am pledging to complete 40 days of fitness to thank Macmillan for being there for me and my family when cancer entered our lives. Diagnosed with breast cancer in July 2019, I know only too well how life altering cancer is, how the support of experts and the kindness of strangers eases the pain. Macmillan were able to help me in my darkest hours, and the words they gave me still guide me now. 

If you pledge a few quid I’d be grateful. I can’t promise great feats of endurance, but I’ll drag my sorry self out every day to earn your support! Thank you.

story:

Throughout this year and especially during the lockdown, Macmillan Nurses have been providing my Granny with immense amounts of support. Please donate anything you can to such an important and vital charity who help those dealing with cancer. I will be running 50 miles/ 80 kilometres over the month of January to encourage people to please donate.

I will be tracking and adding updates about my running progress to the page.

About Macmillan:

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. pageSummary: I am running 54 miles in February because I want to raise money in memory of my Dad.
pageSummaryWhat: I am running 54 miles in February
story:
The 2nd of February marks a very short 10 years since we lost my amazing Dad, I cannot believe it’s been 10 years already and he would’ve been 54 if he was still with us today! To mark this occasion, I’m challenging myself to run 54 miles in February to raise money for MacMillan Cancer care, a charity very close to our hearts. Those who know me will know I am absolutely NOT a runner so although this may not be a challenge for some, it’s a massive challenge for me! For those of you who don’t know our story

My Dad was a fit and healthy man, he didnt smoke and played rugby on a weekly basis. In December of 2010 he suddenly became poorly. He went to the doctors who told him he had a chest infection, and later he was told he had pneumonia. He went into hospital for this but was soon released, however he didn't get much better. He went back to the hospital, and on the 31st of January he was diagnosed with lung cancer. We were heartbroken but knew we needed to make the most of the time we had with him. Unfortunately, we didn't have much time at all, and he passed away on the 2nd of February, only a few days later. Nurses had never seen a case like this before. The time between the diagnosis and his passing was extremely short. I said goodbye to my Dad at the age of only 12, one week before my 13th birthday. It was the worst experience of my life, but fortunately, a Macmillan nurse named Clare helped us immensely. I am so greatful for Clare and the work she did for our family, so I felt I wanted to raise money for the charity in order to give something back to the wonderful team Macmillan have, and also to pay my respects and remember my Dad, who I love and miss more and more everyday. I miss my Dad massively and would do anything I could to get him back, however I know that is impossible and so the closest I can do to that is raise money for Macmillan so they are able to help and support another family like mine, and hopefully make their situation a little easier.

I would really appreciate it if you could take the time to sponsor me. Every single penny counts and I'd love to be able to raise some money for the charity. Thank you for taking the time to read this, lots of love xxx

eventName: Dry January for The British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

In January 2001 I lost my biological Dido - my Daddy Ken, the man that bought me up as his own!

I could never ever repay all he did for me and gave up to give me the life I had - but let's start by raising a little moooolar for this charity!

 BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

pageSummary: We are raising money because We sadly lost our mum to coronary artery disease
story:
On 22nd December our life was turned upside down and we lost Our fantastic mum, dad lost his amazing wife and our children lost their loving nan. 

Her passing came as a huge shock and was extremely sudden. Although we tried along with the Wales Ambulance Crew ( who were fantastic and worth their weight in gold)  sadly mum could not be saved and she gained her angel wings at home with her family around her. 

We have now been told that mum had been the victim of Coronary artery disease. This has come as a bit of a shock as she had no indication that there was a problem. 

Due to current restrictions regarding the funeral, we are asking that instead of flowers  from friends , we would like to raise money to The British Heart foundation to help others affected by this disease. 

Mum..... you will always live on in our hearts

Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Eric, Debbie,Sharon & Melanie 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. pageSummary: Being a sensible human because We haven't been sensible humans for a few years
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page

The lovely Jon Jones and I have been drinking more than our fair share of alcohol for the past few years. It has been an enjoyable past time but we both see a need to change our routine and our habits around alcohol. We are doing this anyway and do not expect anyone to donate, we will be donating £100 to my brothers just giving page  at the end of the month regardless but thought we would start a page of our own in case any of you guys feel the urge to donate too. My incredible brother is the one who kickstarted our motivation to make this change. 

Personally my alcohol intake has been pretty awful since my awesome Dad passed away in April. Being very honest I haven't had a day off since. We are not doing this as new years resolution or anything, we are hopefully changing our views on what alcohol means to us. We will be going down to one day per week and using January to donate to keep us motivated. 

Dad passed away partly due to an undiagnosed heart condition and we have chosen this charity in his name.

Thanks for reading xxx

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support.

I decided to do Dry January for my own health which has been poor over the last 12 months and has not been helped by weight gain, bad diet and LOTS of alcohol consumption through lockdown. So I thought why not kickstart the year by cutting out the wine, cider and gin but raise a little money for a charity close to my heart at the same time? I’ll also be doing the 30 day walkabout challenge. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives and there are also those who still struggle with the disease daily, my Dad being one of them. Despite his bad heart, he continues to push himself every day and refuses to give in to his bad health. He amazes us all with his strength and determination (we say stubbornness!).

It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. 

Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
pageSummary: Im giving up chocolate because Ive got a holey heart thats going to be fixed
story:
Everyone knows my story.

1 major stroke 1992

1 mini stroke. 2018

Then we find out in 2018 I've got a holey heart. This is very common and usually they dont have to do anything. But as you know Im not normal. So in readiness for this procedure I'm giving up my one of my beloved things. 

Chocolate!!

All in a good cause. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: Running because heart disease affects my loved ones.
story:
So 2020 was a pretty tough year for everyone. During lockdown 1.0 the realisation came that my job was ridiculously sedentary!  Like many others.. I became a "covid" runner.  I never thought I would say this, but I quickly realised running gave me the clarity of mind and the me time I so desperately needed.Needing a target to work towards, I signed up for the London Landmarks half-marathon (on my before I turn 40 bucket list)! Yikes!!  

It was a no-brainer that I would be doing this to raise money for the British Heart Foundation.  The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. Sadly, cardiac disease has hit my family hard in the past 12ish months and the only thing I can do to help is encourage my friends and family to support me to raise money so that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures.  

£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist.  £50 helps buy vital lab equipment and £300 helps pay for one day of a project to build new heart tissue that could be used in the future to treat heart failure.  The future is bright!

Every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my £2000 fundraising target. Thanks!

story: Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children STARTS HERE.

Any donation will be appreciated and help me stay motivated to get fit!

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Following on from the huge generosity from Ludgershall village on Christmas Eve during Santa’s visit and requests to donate further we have set up this JustGiving page.


Thank you all so much for your contributions, which really show the true spirit of our village especially during these unprecedented times! Any charitable donations have been split between Mind UK and Great Ormond Street.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story: Our little man, Thomas is currently under the care of this truly amazing hospital. Thomas has a rare birth defect, but thanks to the specialists at GOSH, he has received the surgery needed and is doing well. GOSH really is the centre of excellence for treating children with rare and/or complex health conditions. It was so reassuring when Thomas was referred to GOSH to meet the consultant who had extensive experience of the defect - we are very lucky to have the NHS and the level of expertise and specialisms of those who work within it. Thomas and I have had several trips to the hospital and have witnessed first hand the genuine kindness of the staff and the amazing set up of the hospital. It really is the little things that make the difference, such as each room/bay having a TV that can access YouTube and cbeebies (being able to play stickman was a god send in distracting Thomas when having his obs), to the play specialists (solely funded by the charity) and the range of toys they were able to use to engage with Thomas when he was upset because his stitches were hurting or he was hungery due to fasting prior to CT/MRI or surgery. The NHS funds the running costs of the hospital but it's the charity that funds the vital elements such as research, ensuring access to latest technologies and specialist areas such as the activity rooms. Therefore this January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for GOSH. After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever. Please donate it you can, every penny counts, but I appreciate this year has been difficult for many. Thankyou Kim and Thomas xxx

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Jean supported Great Ormond St Hospital all her life , they saved her Grandson, Josh’s life on several occasions and after 15 years and countless surgeries , they finally fixed him. Josh is now tube free and leads a normal life thanks to this amazing place. Please honour Jean by supporting this amazing cause that was so important to her xx

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

We’re two sisters who started running during the March 2020 lockdown and have carried on. Our year (2020) was brightened by the birth of my sister’s second granddaughter who within a few weeks of birth needed the care of the excellent staff at GOSH. We’re looking for a new challenge to kickstarting 2021 and are taking part in Running off Christmas to raise money for GOSH so other children will continue to benefit from this great institution. We’ll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). pageSummary: 500 virtual walk all the way home! because of the outstanding work they do
pageSummaryWhat: 500 virtual walk all the way home!
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page

2020 has been tough for everyone – some far more than others. Due to COVID-19 2020 will be the first year I have not been in Scotland for New Years celebrations. So, to kick 2021 off I plan to virtually walk and run the 500 miles from my house in Stevenage to my Mum’s house in Stonehaven; aiming to average 5 miles a day for 100 days. Hopefully by the end of those 100 days we might be in a better position to see each other again.

I'll post weekly updates on my progress, using Google StreetView images to show where I'd be if I was actually walking the whole way home on this blog http://malcolms2s.wordpress.com

COVID-19 has impacted our normal way of life, but that hasn’t stopped young children falling ill and needing medical support. Great Ormond Street hospital (www.gosh.org) is one of the world’s leading children’s hospitals, and it’s research and life-changing treatments benefit significantly from public donations.

I’m hoping to get £5 each from 100 people to reach this goal, using JustGiving

pageSummary: Raising money for Cancer Research because to help funding finding cure.
story:
I am sure you have all encountered an experience with the dreaded C. I lost my dad in 2002 which broke my heart! Then in 2014 lost my father-in-law who was only a couple of months away from retirement and enjoying life. They have been both a role model to me and shaped me as a person who I am today. Hard work and honesty were their mottoes which I try to follow.  Losing them both had a major impact on me and left an emptiness in my heart. I would like to raise funds to support the vital works of Cancer Research and hope that one day we will be able to find a cure for it. 

I am raising £874 pounds for each mile I run. If you can please support me, even if it is only one pound it will make a difference!

pageSummary: I am giving up alcohol and chocolate in January because cancer has touched so many loved ones lives
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up alcohol and chocolate in January
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am asking people to donate to cancer research to support me in giving up chocolate and wine in January- both have become all too regularly turned to this last year so will be tough to give up.  This is in memory of my dad John who died of cancer on January 4th 2004 after a long, brave battle.  He was a gentle, kind man whom I greatly miss and dearly wish could have met my children.  

This challenge is also in support of a close friend and a family member who are currently fighting cancer with great determination and dignity.  Cancer has, in some way, touched the lives of most people we know regardless of age.

I encourage you to honour the memory of people you may have lost or who are still fighting cancer by donating and mentioning their name when you donate.  If you send me a picture, I will try to change the cover picture that day to share your memories.  If you are feeling inspired to take on a challenge, pls use this site to collect your donations and tell people what you have done.  Let's form a  'collective against cancer'

Many thanks in advance.  Let's see what we can do together this January.

eventName: A variety of events as part of my Duke of Edinburgh Silver Award
pageSummary: 6 months of fundraising because I want to stop people suffering from cancer.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Since September 2020 I have been working towards my Silver Duke of Edinburgh Award. To fulfill the volunteering section of the award, I have chosen to spend 6 months fundraising for Cancer Research UK. I have chosen this charity because my mum has suffered from cancer herself and it has had an impact on my life. I want to be able to help other families going through similar experiences.

My plan is to carry out the following events over a six month period:

September - October :  Swimathon - 2.5km

November onwards :  Collection Box - clothes, gifts etc for Charity shop

December :  New Year Dip @ West Lydford, River Brue

January :  Cycle 10km each week for a month

February :  Walk 5km each week for a month

Please will you help me by giving as much as you can to this amazing charity. If you don't want to donate online, you can always send a cheque in the post and my mum will make sure it goes to Cancer Research UK.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Thank you very, very much!

story:
Dad left us on 23 December 2020, one of the ways that we’d like to remember him is through supporting research into cancer and its treatment. 

Dad was diagnosed with stomach cancer in February this year. He was given a terminal prognosis with limited options for treatment. 

Dad put his faith into God, science and medicine, taking life day by day. It was a turbulent rollercoaster and one that had a lot of sharp dips, but with Mum’s continued support he fought it!

The work of charities like Cancer Research UK allowed Dad to spend more time with us. But there is still so much to understand to detect the cancers earlier and increase the very low survival rates. We’d welcome your support for Cancer Research UK to do more research into gastric cancer as well as other types of cancer.

Thank you

Sangeeta, Priya, Sumit, Vivek, Roopa

Sarus, Arya, Aaryan, Ila and Amelia

eventName: 2 legs, 874 miles, virtual John O’Groats to Lands End
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

On 1st February, I’ll be starting my virtual hike of John O’Groats to Lands End for Cancer Research....so what’s in store?

Over 8 weeks, I’ll be marching 874 miles (the distance from the top to bottom of the UK) looking to raise £2,000.  This works out at an average of 16 miles per day, for 56 days, whilst still doing an 8 hr daily shift at work.

So, lots of early 5.30am starts taking longer routes hiking to and from work each day, supplemented by 40 mile marches round Norfolk at weekends. 

So please dig deep for this worthy cause. Great strides are being made, but there are any strains of cancer where survival rates amount to months, if not weeks from diagnosis.  The odds are that if you’re reading this, you know somebody who has been affected by cancer, so there’s really no need to labour the importance of the work Cancer Research UK undertake.

All donations will make a huge difference.

Thank you 😀

pageSummary: We are supporting and raising money because Dad was rarely far from a yellow daffodil
pageSummaryWhat: We are supporting and raising money
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit Francis's JustGiving page.

As we are sure you are aware, Dad sadly passed away on the 15th of December 2020, after beating cancer once but losing a brave battle against a secondary rarer cancer within his central nervous system. Dad was courageous throughout his short illness, continually thinking of others ahead of himself and approaching his illness with the determination and positivity only he can muster.    Dad was truly a unique man, so dear to us and to many others and we are heartbroken to have lost him so soon with so much of life left to explore. 

Marie Curie was a passion of Dad's having lost others so loved and cherished by him to cancer over the years. Dad donated monthly to Marie Curie, planted thousands of bulbs and was rarely without his daffodil on his lapel . 

We'd like to raise money to support Marie Curie to further help the provision of Nurses to help those with terminal cancers.

pageSummary: Fundraiser for Marie Curie because I want to raise awareness.
story:
Hello everyone,

Thank you so much for clicking on my page and for helping my fundraising journey. 

Unfortunately in a year that has brought the nation so much upset and loss, I was among the families that lost loved ones during 2020. I lost my Grandma and Grandad a couple of months apart. My Grandad died because of Miloma in his kidneys. And although some say him and my grandma were sole mates and couldn't bear to live on this planet apart, that emptiness of losing them both in a couple of months stings.The Marie Curie nurses were wonderful to my mum and auntie during the time he was very sick and I am aware of how vital their job is in easing just a bit of that pain for people.

I am not a runner, I can barely run to the end of my drive let alone around London! However, I feel very strongly that these wonderful nurses need our praise and support more than ever right now!

So on the 23rd of May, I will be unboxing some new running trainers, pulling on my lycra and pumping up Spotifys best 'running paylist' in an attempt to run Londons Landmark Half Marathon. To Raise money for Marie Curie and in remembrance of my grandparents. 

Any donations would be very much appreciated!

Take care and wish me luck!!!

Annie x

Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: I'm running the Great North Run because I want to help raise vital funds.
pageSummaryWhat: I'm running the Great North Run
story:
In the summer of 2018 my Mum was diagnosed with Breast Cancer requiring palliative care. This has had a massive impact on everything with people such as my dad having to take an active carers role to help in almost every facet of life.

This is why I am running he Great North Run. You can see the impact charities such as Marie Curie Cancer have as I know there specific information manuals and advice have been a significant help for me and their services help so many people in similar situations.

The great north run will be quite has hard as the only sport I have played recently is darts and I don’t think that and pints are adequate training for a half marathon but it is nothing in comparison to the struggle so many people with cancer face every day and it is the strength of people like my mum I want to channel in order to complete this in a respectable time but more importantly raise money for a good cause.

I hope people can be kind enough to donate and help this great cause and help people out in one of the toughest situations someone can face.

pageSummary: I am swimming in the sea in on New Year's Day because I am so grateful for what they do
pageSummaryWhat: I am swimming in the sea in on New Year's Day
story: The single thing that has helped me cope with this freak out of a year has been sea swimming - all summer and right through into winter. Cold water swimming is an amazing thing, you feel incredible - but the sea can be dangerous at any time of year. I'm careful about when I go in, but you never know. Two people have drowned near where I swim this year. So I am always grateful to the amazing volunteers of the RNLI. I am dedicating this swim to my father, because he was a keen sailor and a great fan and supporter of the lifeboat service.

pageSummary: This page is set up to remember Alan E Holland because this was his favourite charity
pageSummaryWhat: This page is set up to remember Alan E Holland
story:
Dad/ Alan Edward Holland died on Christmas Eve, with a great sense of timing and occasion -  on our mother's birthday! He had a very tough time at the end but he was insistent that he stayed at home.  His wishes were for any donations in lieu of floral tributes should go to the RNLI to support his father's time in the Trinity Pilots in Gravesend, so it was always a charity close to the family's heart - along with the fact that Alan never learned how to swim.

Having been an avid chorister all his life - we will be singing outside the church in true Holland style, to celebrate his life on 8th January 2021, at 11.00. The bells shall be ringing - which he and mother put so much effort into restoring with the Friends of Cobham Church. Sadly, during this pandemic - we are limited to a very small guest list and therefore we have set up this page in his memory.

During his life, he studied zoology and biology at Edinburgh and he became a pharmaceuticals marketing manager - selling to the Middle East and around the globe for many years and then went on to enjoy entertaining young minds as the Head of Science at Kings Rochester.  A keen competitive gardener and singer throughout his life - he had a wonderful relationship with Elizabeth and with his grandchildren Max and Isobel. 

Even in these weird times, we must try to celebrate his extraordinary life.  He was an incredible traditionalist, but he is going to have to cut us some slack, as in these extraordinary times - we must adapt to the circumstances. We will endeavour to record some of the service as we know so many would like to attend.

With our very best wishes, and appreciation for all yoru support

Duncan Holland and Claire Edwards


Thank you for visiting our JustGiving page. RNLI lifeboats in the South East protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. From the stunning Dorset, Sussex and Kent coastlines to the unpredictable tidal Thames, our favourite places in the South east are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.The RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea.

RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
We are a team of six open water swimmers who are taking on an epic challenge in September 2021. Starting our relay swim from Nanjizal Beach in Cornwall, England, we will head out of the English Channel and into the Atlantic Ocean for a 29 mile journey across the sea to the Isles of Scilly. To date, no relay team has ever completed this feat.

A challenge like this requires a huge amount of training and preparation and along the way we will inevitably be dealing with hypothermia, jellyfish stings, injury and worst of all - self doubt. But we aim to pull together as a team and deal with whatever is thrown at us and ultimately land successfully in the Scilly Isles. 

The charity we are fundraising for is the Royal National Lifeboat Institution (RNLI). To show your support of our historic challenge, please give generously to help fund the brave men and women who risk their own lives at sea to save those of others.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

pageSummary: I am walking because a diverse & healthy planet matters
story:
A couple of months ago I turned 30 but now shockingly I seem to be turning 60, not sure how that happened. To celebrate, I want to support one of the many organisations that is trying to ensure that the next generation and following generations can reach their 60th birthdays, watered, fed with a diverse wild life that is as interesting as it is amazing.

I am going to walk 60 miles by the  Big Winter Wander on 24th January, and complete 100 by the end of the month.

Any contribution would be much appreciated, and for those who may have thought of a pressie, I don't need stuff, but I do need a planet.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
Name: The Big Winter Wander

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
The latest in WWF’s flagship research series, the Living Planet Report, shows that our planet’s wildlife populations have now plummeted by 68% since 1970 – and there are no signs that this downward trend is slowing.

Half of all UK species are in decline – we’re losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. When nature suffers, we all suffer. But we have a prescription, and if we act now we can protect our health and the health of our planet. 

By supporting The Big Winter Wander, you can help protect our country’s beautiful wildlife. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world.

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

pageSummary: Streaming drawing because I want to see a better future for our planet
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am an artist who loves to draw animals. I have a border collie called Chester, a gargoyle gecko called Jupiter and a western hognose called Udon you may see them during my streams. The environment and animals are very important to me and my values. I prefer to do animal portraits and draw fantasy creatures/cryptids. I also enjoy doing pixel art.

I also love gaming and have doing gaming events in the past to earn money for SpecialEffect some of my personal favourites are: League of Legends, Animal Crossing, Stardew Valley, Terraria, Minecraft, TFT, Skyrim, Magicite, Enter the Gungeon, Don't Starve, Legend of Zelda games, Mario Kart, Mariomaker and Starbound

I also have CFS, chronic migraine, ASD and dyspraxia and may do events for those causes in the future. My stream times may vary because of this to accommodate for my disabilities.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
pageSummary: I am drinking only tap water throughout January because everyone deserves clean, accessible water.
pageSummaryWhat: I am drinking only tap water throughout January
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.

In order to help to get that final figure as big as possible, I have decided to take on a challenge...I am only allowed to drink tap water for the whole of January! 
I did this challenge a few years ago, but having hot mugs of water and unflavored sparkling water really helped me along!
I wanted to go the whole hog this year: only allowing myself to have water fresh from the tap! 

Wateraid is the first-ever charity that I decided to set up a direct debit for each month, and so it is a special charity to me. 
Any amount of donation would be amazing. I know we have all had a tough 2020, so even a small donation would be greatly appreciated.

charity.name: WaterAid
pageSummary: I am drinking just water throughout January because everyone deserves access to a clean water supply
pageSummaryWhat: I am drinking just water throughout January
story:
This is my third year of taking part in Just Water - am I glutton for punishment? 

Not only is Just Water the ultimate detox after an over-indulgent Christmas, but by fundraising for WaterAid I can help to change lives with the gift of clean water.

Today, there are almost 800 million people around the world who have no access to clean water. Dirty water muddies everything from health care to education. By raising money for WaterAid, we can change that and help bring clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene to everyone everywhere.

Last year was hard! As a tea-addict, I struggled during the first couple of weeks but it got easier and it di help me develop better habits for the rest of the year. I'm hoping this year will be easier, but time will tell!

pageSummary: I’m raising money because I believe everyone needs access to clean water
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.
